{"cursor":"11378","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"Lead line}}\n\n\n\nA 'lead', 'lead line', 'lead rope' (USA) or 'head collar rope' (UK), {{cite\nbook|author=R. S. Summerhays|title=Summerhays' Encyclopedia for Horsemen\n|year=1952, revised edition 1962|publisher=Frederick Warne & Co.\nLtd.|address=London, England}} is used to lead an animal such as a horse.\nUsually, it is attached to a halter. The lead may be integral to the halter or,\nmore often, separate. When separate, it is attached to the halter with a heavy\nclip or snap so that it can be added or\nremoved as needed. A related term, 'lead shank' or 'lead chain' refers to a\nlead line with a chain attached that is used in a variety of ways to safely\ncontrol possibly difficult or dangerous horses if they will not respond to a\nregular lead.\n","linknr":288,"url":"Lead_shank","recorded":1362476868,"links":25,"instances":["knot","leg","horse","horse","horse_show"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Horse tack"],"headings":["Variations","Use","Safety in leading","Tying","Use of a shank","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/Horse_in_halter_-_1.jpg/170px-Horse_in_halter_-_1.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/Horse_stub.jpg/220px-Horse_stub.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Cobra_de_juments.jpg/220px-Cobra_de_juments.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2b/Company_200820629P1.jpg/220px-Company_200820629P1.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4d/Strong_little_thing.jpg/220px-Strong_little_thing.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png",